<TITLE> Bush congratulates Spain's Zapatero on election win </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MADRID, March 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - US President George W Bush telephoned Spanish Prime Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero on Friday to congratulate him on his election victory in a sign testy relations between the two may be improving. Spain's Socialist government withdrew troops from Iraq following Zapatero's first election win in 2004, putting a chill on relations between Washington and Madrid. "We spent time chatting about the NATO summit in Bucharest, naturally about subjects that affect shared interests, also on questions about the international order," Zapatero told reporters at a news conference at a European Union summit in Brussels. Bush chose Spain as the starting point for his first European tour in 2001, underlining close ties with former conservative Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, however he has not visited since Zapatero took office, nor has he invited Zapatero to the White House. A spokeswoman for Zapatero said Bush made the surprise five minute "courtesy call" a day after the U.S. embassy in Madrid sent Zapatero a letter of congratulation which stated the United States' wish to intensify and reinforce ties with Spain. "We didn't know he was going to call because the White House spokesman some days ago said that Bush was going to congratulate him and we thought that would simply be the letter," the spokeswoman said, adding that she did not know whether the two had spoken on the telephone previous
